{"title_page": "List of epidemics", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent addition of [[WP:INTREF|unsourced or poorly sourced content]]|small=yes}}\n{{short description|A list of death tolls due to infectious disease}}\n{{Infobox event\n| title                    = List of deaths caused by infectious disease\n| image                    = File:1607-35 Pesttafel Augsburg anagoria.JPG\n| image_size               = 150px\n| caption            = 17th-century German \"plague panel\" depicting the triumph of death. Panels of this kind were placed on the walls of houses to warn against the plague. A plague epidemy raged in Augsburg, Bavaria between 1607 and 1636.\n| image_upright            = \n| image_alt                = \n'''. 1607\u20131635, [[Deutsches Historisches Museum|Deutsches Historisches Museum Berlin]]\n| duration                 = Human history\n| participants             = \n| outcome                  = \n|             = \n| casualties2              = \n| casualties3              = \n}}\n\nThis article is a list of known epidemics caused by an [[infectious disease]].  Widespread [[non-communicable diseases]] such as [[cardiovascular disease]] and [[cancer]] are not included.\n[[File:Emergency hospital during Influenza epidemic, Camp Funston, Kansas - NCP 1603.jpg|thumb|left|Emergency hospital during ''Spanish Influenza'' epidemic, Camp Funston, Kansas (1918-20)]]\n{{clear}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! data-sort-type=\"number\"| Death toll (estimate)\n! Location\n! data-sort-type=\"isoDate\"| Date\n! Event\n! Disease\n! Ref.\n|-\n|data-sort-value=\"0\"|Unknown\n|[[Babylon]], or Babirus of the [[Persia| Persians]], [[Central Asia]], [[Mesopotamia]] and [[Southern Asia]]\n|data-sort-value=\"-1200\"|1200 BC\n|[[Influenza]] [[Epidemic]]\n|[[India| Indian]] [[Sanskrit]] scholars found records of a disease resembling the [[Flu]].\n|<ref name=\"flu\">Mouritz, A. (1921). ''[http://www.gutenberg.org/ebooks/61607/ The Flu]''. Retrieved April 5, 2020.